My definition for bankruptcy is that if a given firm sales disappear from the database or drops 90% or more in the next year (for 2015) + sales are not given or not rise back to the same level as it is in 2014 the next year (for 2016) I indicate my firm as bankrupt.

See this condition below:

#Conditon for bankruptcy:
data_for_flag <- data_for_flag[, bankrupt := ifelse(sales_difference_percent_2015_2014 <= 0.1 & sales_difference_percent_2016_2014 <= 0.1, 1, 0)]

Merging back to the full data:

CREATING MODELS:

Logit with GLMnet model:

1st I create a logit model, with lots of variables. I use poly functions for the continuous variables as I do not know their exact functional forms I decided to use poly-3 for the modeling.

glmnet_model <- train(bankrupt_yes_no ~ poly(curr_assets, 3) +
                        poly(curr_liab, 3) +
                        poly(curr_liab_minus_asset, 3) +
                        poly(founded_year, 3) +
                        poly(ceo_count, 3) +
                        origin +
                        gender +
                        ind +
                        region_m +
                        poly(sales_2014, 3) +
                        poly(sales_2013, 3) +
                        poly(sales_2012, 3)+
                        poly(sales_2011, 3) +
                        poly(sales_2014, 3) +
                        poly(sales_difference_percent_2014_2013, 3) +
                        poly(sales_difference_percent_2013_2012, 3) +
                        poly(sales_difference_percent_2012_2011, 3) +
                        poly(profit_loss_year_2014, 3) +
                        poly(profit_loss_year_2013, 3) +
                        poly(profit_loss_year_2012, 3) +
                        poly(profit_loss_year_2011, 3) +
                        poly(profit_loss_difference_percent_2014_2013, 3) +
                        poly(profit_loss_difference_percent_2013_2012, 3) +
                        poly(profit_loss_difference_percent_2012_2011, 3),
                   method = "glmnet",
                   metric = "ROC",
                   data = data_train,
                   trControl = trainControl(method = "cv",
                                            number = 5,
                                            classProbs = TRUE,
                                            summaryFunction=twoClassSummary),
                   tuneLength=5)

tune_grid <- data.frame("cp" = c(0.0001, 0.0005, 0.001, 0.002, 0.005, 0.01, 0.1))

rpart_model <- train(bankrupt_yes_no ~ curr_assets +
                        curr_liab +
                        curr_liab_minus_asset +
                        founded_year +
                        ceo_count +
                        origin +

                   trControl = trainControl(method = "cv",

Plot together:

thresholds <- seq(0, 1, by = 0.001)

test_truth <- data_test$bankrupt_yes_no

true_positive_rates_glm <- rep(0, length(thresholds)) 
false_positive_rates_glm <- rep(0, length(thresholds))

true_positive_rates_tree <- rep(0, length(thresholds)) 
false_positive_rates_tree <- rep(0, length(thresholds))

true_positive_rates_rf <- rep(0, length(thresholds)) 
false_positive_rates_rf <- rep(0, length(thresholds))

for (ix in 1:length(thresholds)) {
  thr <- thresholds[ix]
  test_prediction_glm_net <- ifelse(data_test$gmlnet_bankrupt_prob > thr, "Yes", "No")
  test_prediction_glm_net <- factor(test_prediction_glm_net, levels = c("Yes", "No"))
  
    test_prediction_tree <- ifelse(data_test$tree_bankrupt_prob > thr, "Yes", "No")
  test_prediction_tree <- factor(test_prediction_tree, levels = c("Yes", "No"))
  
  test_prediction_rf <- ifelse(data_test$rf_bankrupt_prob > thr, "Yes", "No")
  test_prediction_rf <- factor(test_prediction_rf, levels = c("Yes", "No"))
  
  cm <- as.matrix(confusionMatrix(test_prediction_glm_net, test_truth))
  cm2 <- as.matrix(confusionMatrix(test_prediction_tree, test_truth))
  cm3 <- as.matrix(confusionMatrix(test_prediction_rf, test_truth))
  
  true_positive_rates_glm[ix] <- cm[1, 1] / (cm[1, 1] + cm[2, 1])
  false_positive_rates_glm[ix] <- cm[1, 2] / (cm[1, 2] + cm[2, 2])
  
  true_positive_rates_tree[ix] <- cm2[1, 1] / (cm2[1, 1] + cm2[2, 1])
  false_positive_rates_tree[ix] <- cm2[1, 2] / (cm2[1, 2] + cm2[2, 2])
  
  true_positive_rates_rf[ix] <- cm3[1, 1] / (cm3[1, 1] + cm3[2, 1])
  false_positive_rates_rf[ix] <- cm3[1, 2] / (cm3[1, 2] + cm3[2, 2])
  
} 


roc1 <- data.table("threshold" = thresholds,
                   "true_positive_rate" = true_positive_rates_glm,
                   "false_positive_rate" = false_positive_rates_glm,
                   "model" = "glm")

roc2 <- data.table("threshold" = thresholds,
                   "true_positive_rate" = true_positive_rates_tree,
                   "false_positive_rate" = false_positive_rates_tree,
                   "model" = "tree")

roc3 <- data.table("threshold" = thresholds,
                   "true_positive_rate"= true_positive_rates_rf,
                   "false_positive_rate" = false_positive_rates_rf,
                   "model" = "rf")

roc_all <- rbind(roc1, roc2, roc3)


ggplot(data = roc_all, 
       aes(x = false_positive_rate,
           y = true_positive_rate,
           color = model)) +
  geom_line(size = 1.2, alpha = 0.5) +
  geom_abline(slope = 1, color = "black", linetype = 2) +
  labs(x="False Positive Rate", y="True Positive Rate")+ ggtitle("ROC for GLM, Tree and RF model predicted probabilities")

RandomForrest model has the highest AUC therefore RandomForrest is the best model considering this method to decide which model is the best on this data.

We also, can compute the area under the curve (AUC):

AUC_glm <- performance(rocr_prediction_glm, "auc")

AUC_tree <- performance(rocr_prediction_tree, "auc")

AUC_rf <- performance(rocr_prediction_randf, "auc")

table0 <- data.table(Models = c("GLM", "Single Tree", "RandomForest"), AUC = c(AUC_glm@y.values[[1]], AUC_tree@y.values[[1]], AUC_rf@y.values[[1]]))

Calibration plot for the RandomForest model:

deciles <- quantile(data_test$rf_bankrupt_prob, prob = seq(0, 1, length = 11))

group <- cut(data_test$rf_bankrupt_prob, deciles, include.lowest = TRUE)

data_test[, prediction_normal_group := group]

calibrateplot <- data_test[, .(N = .N, true_mean_bankrupt = mean(bankrupt), predicted_mean_bankrupt = mean(rf_bankrupt_prob)), by = prediction_normal_group]

ggplot(calibrateplot, aes(x= true_mean_bankrupt, y=predicted_mean_bankrupt)) + geom_point(size = 3, color = "red")+ geom_text(aes(label=prediction_normal_group),hjust=-0.1, vjust=0) + geom_abline(slope = 1, linetype = 2) + coord_cartesian(xlim = c(0, 0.5), ylim = c(0,0.5)) + labs(x="True raton of bankrupt firms", y="Predicted bankrupt firms ratio") + ggtitle("Calibration plot")

We can see that in the center of our graph our model is overestimates and at very right site is underestimates, but all in all from my point of view it is well calibration plot and a well calibrated model.

We also can calculate the brier score of our models and we can compare them:

Define brier score:

BRIER_SCORE <- function(x, true_x) sqrt(mean((x - true_x)^2))

Calculate Brier Score for each model:

brier_glm <- BRIER_SCORE(data_test$gmlnet_bankrupt_prob,data_test$bankrupt)
brier_tree <- BRIER_SCORE(data_test$tree_bankrupt_prob,data_test$bankrupt)
brier_rf <- BRIER_SCORE(data_test$rf_bankrupt_prob,data_test$bankrupt)

#put it to a table:

table1 <- data.table(Models = c("GLM", "Single Tree", "RandomForest"), Brier_Score = c(brier_glm, brier_tree, brier_rf))

kable(table1, align = 'c', digits = 4)
Models Brier_Score
GLM 0.2878
Single Tree 0.2851
RandomForest 0.2653

Lower Brier score is better. Based on this also the RandomForrest model seems the best
